    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Illustrating_compound_inequalities_on_a_number_line">
      <title>Illustrating compound inequalities on a number line</title>

      <activity>
        <title><term>Work in Groups</term></title>

        <p>
          
          <ol>

          <li>

            <p>
              Consider <me>5&lt;x&lt;12.</me>
            </p>

          </li>

          <li>

            <p>
              Write down the two simple inequalities from the compound inequality.
            </p>

          </li>

          <li>

            <p>
              Draw a number line.
            </p>

          </li>

          <li>

            <p>
              Illustrate the two inequalities on the same number line.
            </p>

          </li>

          <li>

            <p>
              Discuss and share with other groups.
            </p>

          </li>

        </ol>

        </p>

      </activity>

      <p>
        <term>Learning Point.</term>
      </p>

      <p>
        Part of a number line that satisfies two linear inequalities is the illustration of a given compound inequality.
      </p>

      <example>

        <statement>

          <p>
            Illustrate the compound inequality <m>4 &lt; y &lt; 8</m> on a number line.
          </p>

        </statement>

        <solution>

          <p>
            <m>4 &lt; y &lt; 8</m> can also be written as <m>y &gt; 4</m> and <m>y &lt; 8</m>
          </p>

        <image>
          <shortdescription>Number line</shortdescription>

            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw number line
                    \draw[thick, ->] (2,0) -- (10,0);
                    
                    % Draw open circles at x=4 and x=8
                    \draw (4,0) circle (3pt);
                    \draw (8,0) circle (3pt);
                    
                    % Draw line segment between 4 and 8
                    \draw[thick] (4,0) -- (8,0);
                    
                    % Label points
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {4};
                    \node[below] at (8,0) {8};
                    
                    % Optional: Add additional number labels
                    \foreach \x in {3,5,6,7,9} {
                        \node[below] at (\x,0) {\x};
                    }
                    
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            
        </image>

        </solution>

      </example>

